  "content": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "Overview"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "This page is to summarize the GIC configuration needed before starting the OS and how to configure an interrupt in RTA-OS for SAIL"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "GIC overview"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "A Generic Interrupt Controller (GIC) takes interrupts from peripherals, prioritizes them, and delivers them to the appropriate processor core"
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "src": "https://inside-docupedia.bosch.com/confluence/download/attachments/embedded-page/CARSFW/2.0%20Arm%20GIC%20Configuration%20and%20How%20to%20configure%20ISR%20for%20SAIL/image-2024-10-24_16-40-34.png?api=v2",
      "alt": "",
      "local_path": "_images/2.0 Arm GIC Configuration and How to configure ISR for SAIL/image-2024-10-24_16-40-34.png"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 3,
      "text": "Interrupt types"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The GIC can deal with four different types of interrupt sources"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": false,
      "items": [
        "Shared Peripheral Interrupt (SPI) . Peripheral interrupts that can be delivered to any connected core",
        "Private Peripheral Interrupt (PPI) . Peripheral interrupts that are private to one core. An example of a PPI is an interrupt from the Generic Timer",
        "Software Generated Interrupt (SGI) . SGIs are typically used for inter-processor communication and are generated by a write to an SGI register in the GIC",
        "Locality-specific Peripheral Interrupt (LPI - not for our Cortex R52"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 3,
      "text": "Private Peripheral Interrupts (PPIs)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "A wired interrupt generated by a peripheral that is specific to a single core. There are 16 PPIs, INTID16-INTID31 , per core"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "PPI INTIDs 16-21, 28, 29, and 31 are not allocated and are made available as top level ports on Cortex R52"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Default PPI Assignments:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "headers": [
        "INTID",
        "PPI"
      ],
      "rows": [
        [
          "30",
          "Non-secure physical timer interrupt"
        ],
        [
          "27",
          "Virtual timer interrupt"
        ],
        [
          "26",
          "Hypervisor timer interrupt"
        ],
        [
          "25",
          "Virtual CPU Interface Maintenance interrupt"
        ],
        [
          "24",
          "Cross Trigger Interface interrupt"
        ],
        [
          "23",
          "Performance Monitor Counter Overflow interrupt"
        ],
        [
          "22",
          "Debug Communications Channel interrupt"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 3,
      "text": ""
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 3,
      "text": "Shared Peripheral Interrupts (SPIs)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "A wired interrupt generated by a peripheral that is routed to one specific core. Routing is configured by software programming the routing information for that SPI. Up to 960 SPIs are configurable."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The SPIs are identified as INTID32-INTID991"
    },
    {
      "type": "panel",
      "panel_type": "info",
      "title": "Low Latency interrupts",
      "content": "For each of the cores in a processor, 32 unique SPIs are routed to that core using low latency hardware. The same SPIs route to all other cores using normal latency hardware. For corex, INTID(32x+32) to INTID(32x+63) are low latency, where x=0, 1, 2, or 3. For example, for core 1, INTID64-INTID95 are low latency"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 3,
      "text": "Software Generated Interrupts (SGIs)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "SGIs are generated by writing to an SGI generation system register in the GIC CPU interface. There are 16 SGIs, INTID0-INTID15 , that can be generated for each core. An SGI has edge triggered properties. The software triggering of the interrupt is equivalent to the edge transition of the interrupt signal on a peripheral input"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 3,
      "text": "Target settings in Initialization:"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "configure_gic() shall be called before Start OS which will wakeup GIC controller and clear all interrupts and Configure SPIs to Interrupts"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "This configuration is only for th e first physical core in a cluster"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Os_InitializeVectorTable (shall be called be each core) will then configure the INTID in GIC as per our configuration in RTA-OS tool"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 3,
      "text": "How to configure a ISR for particular peripheral"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "we can find the mapping of peripheral to INTD in below document"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "For example, Interrupts for CAN is"
    },
